<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
I. Description of the Source Category 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 112 of the Act requires the EPA to evaluate and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
control emissions of HAP. The control of HAP is to be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
achieved through promulgation of emission standards under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sections 112(d) and (f) for major source categories and such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
minor sources as deemed appropriate that emit HAP. Pursuant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to section 112(c) of the Act, the EPA published in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=4 -->
Federal Register
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 the initial list of source categories that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emit HAP on July 16, 1992 (57 FR 31576). This list includes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
both ``major'' and ``area'' sources (as defined by the Act) that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the EPA intends to regulate before November of the year 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2000. The initial list of source categories includes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``Shipbuilding and Ship Repair (Surface Coating),'' the major 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sources only, as a source category. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For the purpose of the proposed rule, shipbuilding and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ship repair refers to all facilities that build, repair, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
paint, repaint, convert, or alter ships. (Hereafter, this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
industry will be referred to as ``shipbuilding.'') A ship is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
defined as any marine or fresh-water vessel used for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
military or commercial operations, including self-propelled 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
vessels, those towed by other craft (barges), and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
navigational aids (buoys). This definition includes, but is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not limited to, all military vessels, commercial cargo and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
passenger (cruise) ships, ferries, barges, tankers, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
container ships, patrol and pilot boats, and dredges. It 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
does not include offshore oil and gas drilling platforms, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
although it is believed that identical coating systems would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be appropriate for them also. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
II. Background 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The proposed rule represents the EPA's first extensive 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulation of air pollutants from the shipbuilding and ship 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
repair industry. Essentially all volatile organic hazardous 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
air pollutants (VOHAP) are a subset of a category of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pollutants referred to as volatile organic compounds (VOC). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The VOC is a class of pollutants that are photochemically 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reactive precursors of ozone. Emissions of VOC (and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consequently VOHAP as well) from ``marine coating operations'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have been regulated by some State and local district rules. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
California and Louisiana have defined VOC limits for a wide 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
range of marine coating categories. The California limits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
being generally more stringent than those of Louisiana. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Other States have limited VOC emissions from the industry's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
spray booths as one of many ``miscellaneous metal coating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
operations,'' using guidance presented in the EPA's control 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
techniques guidelines (CTG) document ``Control of Volatile 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Organic Emissions from Existing Stationary Sources, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Volume VI: Surface Coating of Miscellaneous Metal Parts and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Products'' (June 1978) EPA 450/2&hyph;78&hyph;015. Outdoor painting of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ships' hulls was specifically exempt from this guidance, but 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
some States have rules that limit shipyard painting done 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
inside buildings and on the interior of ships based on the guidance. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
