<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Control Techniques Guidelines 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 183(b)(4) of the Act, as amended in 1990 (1990 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Amendments), requires the Administrator to issue CTG's for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
VOC and particulate emissions from coatings (paints) and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
solvents used in shipbuilding and ship repair facilities, to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such level as the Administrator determines may be achieved 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
through the adoption of BACM. Volatile organic compounds 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
react in the atmosphere to form ozone, a criteria air 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pollutant for which primary and secondary ambient air 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
quality standards have been established. The EPA is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
required to take into account the applicable requirements of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section 112 in developing the guidelines. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The organic HAP emissions described in the remainder of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this document are, with only one exception, a subset of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
VOC emissions from coatings and solvents used in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
shipbuilding and ship repair facilities. Thus the control 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
techniques evaluated for the MACT standard are also 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicable to VOC emissions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The EPA has traditionally issued draft CTG's containing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recommended control levels for public comment. Rather than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
issue a separate draft CTG in this case, the EPA is using 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this document to request public comment on a draft 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recommended by BACM. The recommended BACM is identical to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the proposed MACT for coatings and solvents, stated in terms 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of VOC units rather than VOHAP units (where a VOHAP means 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
any compound of carbon, excluding metallic carbides and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
carbonates, that is listed in or pursuant to section 112(b) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the Act; this includes both VOC and exempt compounds that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are listed as HAP). For those options using VOC as a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
surrogate for VOHAP for the MACT standard, compliance would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be based on the Agency's reference Method 24. For any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
compliance option involving measurement of actual VOHAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
content, the test method used by the source must be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
documented and approved by the Administrator. Comments 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
received on the proposed MACT rule will also be considered 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in formulating a final recommended BACM and vice-versa. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Meanwhile, States are in the process of developing VOC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rules for these sources to meet other Act requirements. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA published an alternative control techniques (ACT) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
document in February 1994 to provide guidance to the States 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for these efforts. The recommended BACM described here is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consistent with information in the ACT. Also, as explained 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the ACT, although control technologies for particulate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions at shipyards are in development, none are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sufficiently demonstrated at this time to recommend as BACM. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Therefore, the Agency has no recommendation for BACM for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
particulate emissions at this time. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
III. Summary of the Proposed Rule 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
A. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=3 -->
Applicability 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=3 -->
1. Description of the Source Category 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
The proposed rule would apply to each shipbuilding 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
facility whose total activities emit or have the potential 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to emit, considering controls, 9.1 megagrams per year 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(Mg/yr) (10 tons per year [tons/yr]) or more of any HAP or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
22.7 Mg/yr (25 tons/yr) or more of any combination of HAP. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In general, the shipbuilding industry covered by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed rule is represented by SIC Code 3731, ``Shipbuilding 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and Repairing.'' This industry consists of establishments 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that build, repair, repaint, convert, and alter ships. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
However, SIC Code 3731 includes the manufacture of both 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
offshore oil and gas well drilling and production platforms; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
marine coatings used on such platforms will not be subject 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to this rule, but rather to limitations imposed by the EPA's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Federal rule on Architectural and Industrial Maintenance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Coatings. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Based on information obtained through the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
U. S. Maritime Directory Listings (June 1992), there are an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
estimated 437 facilities of varying capabilities involved in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the construction and repair of ships in the United States. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Of the 437 facilities, an estimated 25 qualify as major 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sources of HAP emissions and would be subject to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed rule. The total VOHAP emissions from surface 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coating operations at the 25 facilities that would be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subject to the proposed rule are estimated at 1,155 Mg/yr 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1,272 tons/yr).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
