<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=3 -->
B. Air Emission Reductions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
The nationwide baseline VOHAP emissions for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
approximately 25 major shipbuilding facilities from surface 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coating operations are estimated to be 1,155 Mg/yr 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1,272 tons/yr). Implementation of the proposed standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would reduce these emissions by approximately 24 percent to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
883 Mg/yr (972 tons/yr). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=3 -->
C. Secondary Environmental Impacts 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
No environmental impacts to water, solid waste, noise, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or secondary air impacts are associated with implementation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the proposed standards, as explained below. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=3 -->
1. Water 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
There are no negative water pollution impacts resulting 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
from transition to compliant coatings. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=3 -->
2. Solid Waste 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
There are no negative solid waste impacts associated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with the proposed standards. No additional or new types of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
solid or hazardous waste will be generated. Because the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
compliant (higher solid) coatings are more concentrated, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fewer containers will require disposal when the same volume 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of solids is applied. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=3 -->
3. Noise 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
There is no additional noise associated with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed standards. Pumps and compressors, the source of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the majority of the noise in paint operations, is not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
expected to change. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=3 -->
4. Secondary Air Impacts 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
There are no significant secondary air pollution 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impacts. Use of compliant coatings avoids use of any type 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of control device or equipment that would consume large 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
amounts of energy. Furthermore, any reduction in VOC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions that result from compliance with the HAP rule will 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reduce both ozone formation and CO
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=2 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
, a greenhouse gas (VOC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that remain airborne react to form ozone and are ultimately 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
oxidized to CO
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=2 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
D. Energy Impacts 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Paint heaters are now used in some shipyards. Some 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sources may use paint heaters in lieu of solvent to reduce 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
paint viscosity. Although some secondary air impacts would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result from the power requirements of the electrical 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
heaters, the amount of electricity that they draw is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
insignificant. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
E. Cost Impacts 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The incremental nationwide annual costs associated with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the proposed standards (MACT cost minus baseline cost) is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
approximately $1.7 million per year. The use of compliant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coatings will not require different equipment. Because 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
lower-VOC (and presumably lower-VOHAP) coatings are more 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
concentrated, less coating volume is required to cover the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
same surface area to the same dry film thickness. Some of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
these compliant coatings, however, may be more expensive 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
both on a dollar-per-gallon basis, but also in cost-per- 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
volume solids (nonvolatiles). Therefore, the annual costs 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
associated with the proposed standards reflect the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
difference between the costs of higher-priced coatings and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the savings associated with the decreased volume of coatings 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(because of the higher solids content) and labor to apply 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
them. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Minor costs would be incurred by any source that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
purchases paint heaters or other minor equipment necessary 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to comply with the handling, transfer, and storage standard. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
These costs are expected to be insignificant. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
F. Economic Impacts 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Economic impacts were calculated on a facility-specific 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
basis as well as on a market segment basis (i.e., military 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
construction, commercial repair, etc.). Economic impact 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
indicators examined included price, output, and employment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impacts. The economic impact analysis calculated economic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impacts for six market segments within the shipbuilding and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
repair industry. Two methods were used to calculate the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
potential price impacts; therefore, these impacts will be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provided in terms of ranges. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Twenty major-source yards were identified as first-tier 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
shipyards (facilities that have the capability to construct, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
drydock, and/or topside repair vessels with a minimum 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
overall length of 400 feet). Two market segments in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
first tier, facilities engaging in construction of military 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ships and privately owned facilities engaging in repair of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
military ships, are each estimated to increase their prices 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
0.1 percent or less to recover increased costs of the rule. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The cost for the third market segment, government-owned 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
shipyards engaging in repairing military ships, will be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
negligible. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The remaining five major-source shipyards are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
categorized into the ``second tier'' (facilities building and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
repairing ships less than 400 feet in length). Within this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
tier, the market segment consisting of facilities 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
constructing ships for the military is estimated to require 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a price increase between 0.1 and 0.2 percent. The market 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
segment consisting of facilities engaging in construction of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ships for the commercial sector is estimated to require a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
price increase of 0.3 percent or less. Lastly, the market 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
segment consisting of facilities performing repair on ships 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the commercial sector is expected to require little or no 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
price increase. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The facility-specific impact calculations estimate the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
maximum price increase necessary for a regulated facility to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fully recoup its annualized control costs. For the purposes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the analysis, a facility's price increase was considered 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
significant if greater than 1 percent and deviated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
considerably from its corresponding market segment price 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
increase. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The facility-specific price increase calculations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
indicated that 23 of the 25 major-source shipyards are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
expected to experience price increases of 0.1 percent or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
less. Of the two remaining, one is expected to experience a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
0.2 percent price increase and the other, 0.3 percent.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
