<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1. Reduce the volume of, or eliminate emissions of, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such pollutants through process changes, substitution of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
materials, or other modifications; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 2. Enclose systems or processes to eliminate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 3. Collect, capture, or treat such pollutants when 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
released from a process, stack, storage, or fugitive 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emission point; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 4. Are design, equipment, work practice, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
operational standards including requirements for operator 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
training or certification as provided in section 112(h); or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 5. Any combination of the above [section 112(d)(2)]. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 To develop NESHAP, the EPA collects information about 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the industry, including information on emission source 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
characteristics, control technologies, data from HAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emission tests at well-controlled facilities, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
information on the cost, energy, and other environmental 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impacts of emission control techniques. The EPA uses this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
information to analyze possible regulatory approaches. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Although NESHAP are normally structured in terms of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
numerical emission limits, alternative approaches are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sometimes necessary. In some cases, physically measuring 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions from a source may be impossible or at least 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impracticable due to technological and economic limitations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 112(h) authorizes the Administrator to promulgate a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
design, equipment, work practice, or operational standard or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
combination thereof, in those cases where it is not feasible 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to prescribe or enforce an emissions standard. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 If any sources in the source category are considered 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
major (based on their emissions), then a MACT standard is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
required. To establish a MACT standard, the level of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
control corresponding to the MACT floor needs to be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determined as a starting point for developing the regulatory 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
alternatives. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
C. Categorization/Subcategorization: Determining MACT 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``Floors'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 112 of the Act provides certain very specific 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
directives to guide the EPA in the process for establishing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
MACT standards. It states that the EPA shall establish 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
standards that require ``the maximum degree of reduction in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions of the hazardous air pollutants *
<!-- PJG 0060 hspace -->
&blank;9*
<!-- PJG 0060 hspace -->
&blank;9* that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Administrator, taking into consideration the cost of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
achieving such emission reduction, and any nonair quality 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
health and environmental impacts and energy requirements, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determines is achievable *
<!-- PJG 0060 hspace -->
&blank;9*
<!-- PJG 0060 hspace -->
&blank;9*'' [section 112(d)(2)]. In 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
addition, a minimum baseline or ``floor'' for a standard is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
specified. For new sources, the standard for a source 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
category or subcategory ``shall not be less stringent than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the emission control that is achieved in practice by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
best controlled similar source, as determined by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Administrator'' [section 112(d)(3)]. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Further, standards for existing sources shall be no 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
less stringent than: (1) the average emission limitation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
achieved by the best performing 12 percent of the existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sources in the category or subcategory for categories and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subcategories with 30 or more sources; or (2) the best 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
performing five sources for categories or subcategories with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fewer than 30 sources [section 112(d)(3)]. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Once the floor has been determined for new or existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sources for a category or subcategory, the Administrator 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
must set MACT standards no less stringent. Such standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
must then be met by all sources within the category or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subcategory. However, in establishing standards, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Administrator may distinguish among classes, types, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sizes of sources within a category or subcategory and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
establish a different emission standard for each class, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provided all standards are at least as stringent as the MACT 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
floor. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 The EPA has determined that there are less than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
30 major shipbuilding sources. Consequently, the MACT floor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for existing categories or subcategories was calculated to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be the arithmetic average (the mean) of the emission 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limitation achieved by the best performing five sources. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
D. Regulatory Approach and Regulatory Alternatives 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The next step in establishing standards is the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
investigation of regulatory alternatives. With MACT 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
standards, only alternatives at least as stringent as the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
floor may be considered. Information about the industry is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
analyzed to develop model plant populations for projecting 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
national impacts, including HAP emission reduction levels, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
costs, energy, and secondary impacts. Several regulatory 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
alternative levels (which may be different levels of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions control or different levels of applicability or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
both) are then evaluated to determine the most appropriate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulatory alternative to serve as the basis for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
standard. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 The regulatory alternatives for new versus existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sources may be different, and separate regulatory decisions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
must be made for new and existing sources. For both source 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
types, the selected alternative may be more stringent than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the MACT floor. However, the control level selected as the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
name maximum achievable control technology indicates, must 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be available, i.e., technically achievable. In selecting a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulatory alternative, the Agency considers the achievable 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reduction in emissions of HAP (and possibly other pollutants 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that are co-controlled), the cost and economic impacts, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
energy requirements, and other environmental impacts. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 The selected regulatory alternative is then translated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
into a proposed regulation. The regulation implementing the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
decision typically includes the following sections: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicability, standards, test methods, compliance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
demonstration, monitoring, reporting, and recordkeeping. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The preamble to the proposed regulation provides an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
explanation of the rationale for the decisions embodied in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the rule. The public is invited to comment on the proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulation. Based on an evaluation of these comments, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA promulgates the final standard.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
