<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
VI. Process Description and Control Technologies 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This section describes the painting process and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
technologies that can be used to control organic HAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions from painting operations at shipyards. For more 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
detailed description of the process and control 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
technologies, consult the BID for the proposed standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(see 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
ADDRESSES
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 at the beginning of this Preamble). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Over 99 percent of HAP emissions at shipyards are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
organic solvents associated with paints and cleaning. Other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
activities that collectively contribute the remaining 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1 percent include welding, metal forming/cutting, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
abrasive blasting. The proposed standards will affect 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
operations involving the use of paint and organic solvents. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
A. Painting Process 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Marine coatings are applied to the surface of ship 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
components to form a protective, functional or decorative 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
films. The basic components of a coating are the vehicle 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(resin or binder), solvent, pigment (except in clear 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coatings), and a variety of additives. Different coatings 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are used for different purposes; depending on where it is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applied, the intended use of the ship, ship activity, travel 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
routes, desired time between coatings (service life), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
aesthetic desires of the ship owner or commanding officer, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and fuel costs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Marine coatings are vital for protecting the ship from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
corrosive and biotic attacks from the water environment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Many marine coatings serve specific functions, such as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
corrosion protection, heat/fire resistance, or antifouling 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(to prevent the settlement and growth of marine organisms on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the ship's underwater hull). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 The most popular techniques for applying coatings to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
marine vessels are brushing, rolling, air-atomizing, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
airless spraying. Brushing and rolling are primarily used 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for touchup and recessed surfaces where spraying is not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
practical. Spraying is used for all other surfaces because 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of its high application speed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Thinning solvent is sometimes added to coatings before 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
application even though paint manufacturers state that it is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
unnecessary. Temperature, reportedly can play a big part in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the decision to thin; cold increases paint viscosity. For 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such cases, the appropriate solvent to use for each coating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is specified by the manufacturer. Typically these paints 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and thinning solvents contain one or more of the following 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP: xylene, toluene, and/or methyl ethyl ketone. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
B. Control Technologies for Painting Operations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Emissions of VOHAP result primarily from solvent 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
evaporation_both solvent in the paint ``as supplied'' by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
manufacturer and any solvent used by the shipyard to thin 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the paint. Reaction by-products released during the cure of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
some coatings may also contain HAP. Essentially, all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
organic solvents, including those which are HAP, are emitted 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
either as the paint is applied or when it dries/cures. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
shipyard may limit emissions of HAP from, ``as supplied'' or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``as applied,'' coatings as discussed below.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR941206-1-00103 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR941206-1-00008 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
1. Paints As-Supplied by the Manufacturer 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Since the Agency began its program to reduce emissions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of volatile organics in the late 1970's, the coating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
industry has made significant progress in research of new 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
products with increased solids: organic solvent ratios. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
These liquid paints are of two primary types: waterborne 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and higher solids. Although many new waterborne products 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have been developed, manufacturers of marine coatings have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reduced solvent primarily by increasing the solids 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(nonvolatile) content of their products. Use of these 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
concentrated or ``higher solids'' coatings reduce solvent 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions per surface area painted (at same film thickness). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Because most hazardous air pollutants are also volatile 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
organics, the VOC program has tended to also reduce HAP. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 In addition, some coating manufacturers have reportedly 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
been able to reduce the HAP content of certain paints by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
merely substituting a solvent not on the HAP list yielding 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
paints that contain little or no HAP solvents. A coating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reformulated in this manner may have the same or even higher 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
VOC content than the one it replaces. In some cases, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP to VOC ratio may even increase when a company develops a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
new reformulation with lower VOC. (Note, the absolute HAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions are likely to go down.) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
2. Paints As-Applied by the Shipyard 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
There are several alternatives a shipyard may follow to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
minimize HAP emissions from as-applied paints. One is to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
avoid diluting the paint and apply it as-supplied. Another 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is to only use thinners that contain little or no HAP. A 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
third is to reduce paint viscosity by heating the paint to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
avoid or minimize the need for thinning. (Paint heaters are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
heating elements placed in the paint delivery line upstream 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the spray gun. Depending on the length of the delivery 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
line, the coating characteristics, and ambient temperature, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
multiple paint heaters may be required at intervals along 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the line. These decrease the ease of portability and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
flexibility of the application system.) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 ``Add-on'' pollution control systems are often used to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
control emissions from spray booths when coatings are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applied in factory operations. Such systems are not now a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
practical alternative for many shipyard operations because 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the size of ship components is too large to enable capturing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the emissions with an enclosure. (There is currently 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under development a mobile enclosure that, if successful, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
will offer shipyards a method of capturing both particulate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and volatile organics. Metro Machine shipyard in Norfolk, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Virginia has developed a prototype portable enclosure that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
mounts adjacent to the ship and supports an omni-directional 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
elevator platform used by the operator to abrasive blast and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
paint ship's hulls. The method shows promise of containing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
particulate and volatile organics of concentrations great 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
enough to make recovery available at reasonable cost. It 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
also provides weather protection thereby allowing work to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
continued in inclement weather. Final evaluation will 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
likely be completed in 1996.) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR941206-1-00104 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR941206-1-00008 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
C. Handling, Transfer, and Storage of Volatile Organic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP Containing Materials 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Volatile organic emissions (including HAP) result from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
storage, handling, and transfer of solvents and paint wastes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that contain VOHAP. These solvents, typically stored in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
55-gallon drums, are frequently transferred by pump or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
spigot into small buckets or 1 gallon containers for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
transport to the painting site. Waste solvent and HAP also 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
evaporate from solvent-laden rags and spent solvent used in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cleaning activities and coating operations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 These HAP emissions may be minimized with appropriate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
work practices including managed chemical (paint and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
solvent) distribution systems designed to curb the volume of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
material exposed to the atmosphere and the length of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exposure. For example, solvent-soaked cleaning rags should 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be kept in impervious bags or containers that are normally 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
closed when not in use. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
VII. Selection Rationale 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
A. Selection of Emission Points to be Covered 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The proposed standards would limit VOHAP emissions from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
surface coating operations at shipbuilding facilities that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are major sources in accordance with the EPA's list of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
source categories published in the 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=4 -->
Federal Register
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
July 16, 1992 (57 FR 31576). Standards are being proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to limit the VOHAP content of 23 categories of coatings used 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in shipyards. In addition, the proposed standards would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
require work practice measures for handling, transfer, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
storage of solvent and paint wastes. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Welding, gas freeing (tank degassing), metal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fabrication, fuel combustion, flame cutting, cooling towers, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
asbestos removal, and cleaning would not be regulated under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the proposed rule, although their emissions must be included 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in determining if a facility qualifies as a major source. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Asbestos removal is covered in 40 CFR part 61, subpart M; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cooling towers are treated in the industrial process cooling 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
tower rule proposed on August 12, 1993; and chromium 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions by the rule for hard and decorative electroplating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and anodizing operations proposed on November 30, 1993. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Methodology for determining and managing emissions from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cleaning solvents is detailed in the ACT document_Industrial Cleaning Solvents, EPA&hyph;453/R&hyph;94&hyph;015.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
B. Selection of the Basis for the Proposed Standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The general methodology for selecting the basis for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
MACT standards was discussed in section V. A more detailed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
discussion specific to this industry is presented below. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
1. Coating Operations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
No emission control measures are known to have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
previously been implemented specifically to reduce HAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions from this industry. Regulations that reduce VOC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions will limit HAP emissions since almost all organic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP are VOC. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 At shipyards, the only VOC control measure that has 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
been fully demonstrated for outdoor coating operations is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the use of coatings with inherently lower emissions. Such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coatings have and are being developed by an enlightened 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
industry to reduce its environmental impact. The new 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
products are used for compliance with VOC regulations in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Louisiana and some California jurisdictions. There are as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
yet no known cases where add-on pollution control systems 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have been used to control VOC emissions from outdoor coating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
operations at shipyards. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 The California and Louisiana regulations limit the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
allowable quantity of VOC in each of several categories of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coatings, as applied. Because VOHAP are VOC (with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exception noted above), such regulations also reduce, or at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a minimum, put a ceiling on the allowable HAP content of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
these coatings. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 The California regulations (VOC limits) are more 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
stringent than those in Louisiana. Thus, the major sources 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subject to those California rules represent the ``best 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
controlled sources.'' Because three major source facilities 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are located in California, the single best controlled 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
facility and the median facility of the best performing five 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sources are both subject to the stringent California 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulations. Therefore, the Agency has determined that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
MACT floor for both new and existing sources is identical to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the current California VOC limits on marine coatings, except 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for one additional paint category [weld-through (shop) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
primer]. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR941206-1-00105 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR941206-1-00008 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
A variety of more stringent alternatives were 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
considered, including more restrictive limits based on HAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
content (rather than VOC content), more stringent VOC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limits, and requiring use of pollution control equipment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
These alternatives are discussed below. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 To evaluate other potential limits, the EPA gathered 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
existing data on HAP content from marine coating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
manufacturers and shipyards. Information compiled from a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
material safety data sheet (MSDS) was used to determine 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(estimate) the HAP content of each paint. Most of the data 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
came from MSDSs and product data sheets. Based on these 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
data, the percentage of VOC in marine coatings that are HAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
varies from zero to 100 percent and averaged 30 percent by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
weight for all paints in the project data base. (The HAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
content could exceed the VOC content in coatings containing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
non-VOC HAP.) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Industry subsequently informed EPA that the quality of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP-specific data on MSDSs is poor. The MSDSs are prepared 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
primarily to meet Occupational Health and Safety 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Administration (OSHA) requirements. Although one section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
addresses hazardous constituents, the industry indicated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that information and format required for OSHA purposes are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not as detailed or accurate as would be desired for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
development of a regulation. Further, the list of hazardous 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
materials that OSHA regulations require must be addressed in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
MSDSs is different from the HAP list in section 112(b) of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Act. In addition, it is acceptable to give a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
concentration range on the MSDS, rather than a specific 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
value. Finally, many entries on the MSDS are generic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
petroleum solvents, such as mineral spirits, which are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
mixtures of many organics (some of which may be HAP) and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
vary in composition from lot to lot. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Because of these drawbacks in MSDS data, the EPA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
considered it not accurate enough to be used in setting 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limits for VOHAP. The Agency believes, however, that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
resulting data base is sufficiently accurate for use in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
estimating broad parameters, such as the potential reduction 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
associated with limitations on VOC content. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Enforcement of a limit on HAP content would require an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA reference test method. Although one is under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
development by the Agency, it has not yet been published. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Based on the quality of the HAP content data on the MSDSs 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and the lack of an approved test method for speciating and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
quantifying HAP, the EPA has determined that VOC will be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
used as a surrogate to limit HAP emissions. Consequently, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the proposed rule would establish the VOHAP limit at the VOC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limit of the California rules using VOC as a surrogate for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP and the Agency's VOC test method, Method 24, for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determining compliance. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 The EPA considered requiring limits more stringent than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the existing California limits. The data base indicates 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that within each category of coatings there are coatings 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with VOC contents below the California limit. (Some may 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have been developed in response to the technology-forcing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provisions of the California regulations that provide for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
more stringent limits to come into effect in September 1994 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for some coating categories.) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Although coatings with lower VOC contents than the rule 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requires are marketed in each category, they reportedly 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would not perform for the full range of potential 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applications within a coating category. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 An important consideration in examining control 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements for this industry is U.S. Navy military 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
specifications or ``milspecs.'' Because of the need for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coatings for specialized applications and the demand for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
predictable performance, the Navy oversees exhaustive 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
performance testing procedures. Naval personnel indicate an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ongoing program to qualify lower VOC coatings. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
California rules were developed with considerable input from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Navy, and according to a Naval representative, reflect 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the ``state of the art'' for lower-VOC shipbuilding coatings. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Volatile organic compound limits more stringent than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed would require that the Navy use paints for which 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
they have not yet completed long term testing, hence are not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
milspec approved. Given these considerations, the EPA is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposing MACT emission levels based on the 1992 California 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulations that limit the total VOC as-applied paint. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
