<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The EPA also evaluated the potential of add-on VOC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
control devices (i.e., carbon adsorbers and incinerators). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Although no cases are known where add-on controls are used 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for outdoor painting at shipyards, they have been used to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reduce spraybooth emissions by many other industries. Most 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coating operations at shipyards take place outdoors, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
primarily because of the size of parts painted. This makes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
capture of emissions difficult and expensive. Use of add-on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
controls for outdoor painting was not selected as the basis 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for MACT for these reasons. It should be noted, however, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that a portable enclosure that will contain particulate and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
VOC during abrasive blasting and coating of ships' hulls is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under commercial development. Should these enclosures prove 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
technically and economically feasible, their performance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
should be considered by any State or the Federal Government 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in developing future rules for this industry. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Two types of coating operations at shipyards where 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions are more available to capture were examined more 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
closely for the feasibility of add-on controls: indoor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coating operations and painting inside of ship's tanks or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
other internal enclosed spaces. Based on a brief screening 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
analyses, using the limited available data that assumes all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
spray areas are continually drafted to the control device 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(whether painting operations are underway in all areas or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not), add-on control was estimated to be on the order of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
$150,000/Mg of VOHAP removed. The EPA believes that this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cost is not reasonable for this source category. As a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result, add-on controls were not investigated further nor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
selected as the basis for MACT. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 In reality, the amount of VOC and HAP controlled at a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
site is dependent on the rate of paint application, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
concentration of these compounds in the exhaust air stream 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
during the painting operation, the flow rate of the air 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
stream flowing into the add-on control unit and a host of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
other factors. The suitability of add-on controls can only 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be determined on a case-by-case basis. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 After review of alternatives more stringent than the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
MACT floor, the EPA is proposing to set the MACT standard at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the floor based on the California marine coatings rule which 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is for both new and existing sources. The costs of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
control option for new and existing sources is expected to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be the same. The Agency solicits comments on this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determination. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 ``Models'' of shipyards were developed to help determine 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the need to differentiate among classes of shipyards in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
identifying the MACT.'' Models were developed for classes of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
yards based on market segment (yards that construct ships 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
versus those that only repair) and size (large versus 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
medium). The EPA concluded there is no basis for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
differentiating among classes of major source shipyards, but 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
specifically solicits comments on whether this category 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
should be subcategorized; and if so, how. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
2. Handling, Transfer, and Storage of VOHAP Containing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Material 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Based on information received from industry, a variety 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of ``work practice'' measures are used to reduce evaporative 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
losses of VOC from transfer, handling, and storage of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
solvent and paint wastes. These include spill minimization 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
techniques (use of spouts, funnels, or catch basins during 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
transfer of liquids from one container to another), the use 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of normally closed containers or piping to transport 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
liquids, and the use of close-fitting or tight covers on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
containers for solvent, wet rags, and waste. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 Many more than five facilities employ some type of work 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
practice measures. Facilities in California are subject to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulations to minimize evaporative emissions; other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
facilities employ such measures to decrease solvent usage or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to minimize exposure of workers. However, data to quantify 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
accurately the emission reductions achievable by different 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
work practice measures is unavailable. The beneficial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
effect of a specific change is largely a function of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
previous plant practice being remedied. As a result, even 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
though such activities obviously reduce emissions, there is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
no way to distinguish between the ``best controlled source'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and the ``best performing five existing sources.'' Therefore, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the EPA has designated the same select work practice 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
measures as the MACT floor for control of emissions from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
handling and transfer of VOHAP containing material at both 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
new and existing facilities. For emissions from storage 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
containers, the MACT floor is use of tight-fitting covers 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that must be normally closed; that is, in place except when 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
materials are being added to or withdrawn. The Agency 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
believes that this is a reasonable approach. Because work 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
practice measures typically entail negligible cost, any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emission reduction that is achieved is believed to be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
worthwhile. The EPA specifically solicits comments on this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determination.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
