<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
No other more effective control options for these VOHAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions from cleaning activities were found. Use of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
lower-HAP or lower-vapor-pressure substitutes to minimize 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
evaporative losses may be feasible, although this option 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
depends on the availability of a suitable replacement 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cleaning material. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Capture and control of fugitive emissions from the many 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
transfer, handling, and storage of solvents (and operation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
wastes) although conceivable, is impractical, making it 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
difficult to invoke any quantifiable standard other than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
work practice requirements. Associated monitoring and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recordkeeping are included for determining compliance. In 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
an attempt to ensure that employees understand and comply 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with the requirements, the proposed standards also require 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
each source to implement a training program for all involved 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
personnel. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
C. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=3 -->
Selection of the Format of the Proposed Standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=3 -->
1. Coating Operations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Most HAP emissions from coating operations in this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
industry occur outdoors where the technology for their 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
capture has not been demonstrated. As a result the only 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
available technology for reducing emissions is to require 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
use of coatings with lower volatile content. Virtually all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the HAP and VOC contained in marine coatings are emitted 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to the atmosphere during the course of application and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
drying. Thus, an emission standard based on limiting both 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP and VOC content of the coatings, as applied, is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
appropriate for these operations, particularly because any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
additional HAP and VOC that may be formed and emitted during 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the curing process are detected and measured by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reference measurement methodology. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
As a result, the types of coatings used by the industry 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
were identified and maximum, never-to-be-exceeded HAP limits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
were selected for each of the several coating categories. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
To allow additional flexibility, the ability to average 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limits across categories was also considered. Under an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
averaging approach, any coating regardless of volatile 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
organic content, can be used as long as the volume weighted 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
average as applied VOHAP content, i.e., as measured by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reference method, of all coatings does not exceed the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
average calculated from their individual limits. In 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
developing the limits, the Agency considered two types of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
averages: (1) Separate averages for coating within each of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the coating categories and (2) a single average for all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coatings used by a facility. The option of establishing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limits based on weighted averages of various coatings of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
different pollution content was abandoned when the industry 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
indicated that time and effort to plan, track, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
demonstrate compliance would be too burdensome. As a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result, the limits are based on never-to-be-exceeded VOHAP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contents for 23 categories of coatings and permits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``averaging'' for purposes of compliance under certain 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
conditions. The proposed coating categories and associated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HAP limits are presented in Table 1. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=3 -->
2. Handling, Transfer, and Storage of VOHAP Containing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Material 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
The proposed work practice standards require that these 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
operations be carried out in such a manner that minimizes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
spills. For storage and transport, the proposed standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
require use of containers that are normally closed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
To provide a measure of enforceability to these 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
standards, each source will be required to indicate how it 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
intends to comply with the standards as part of the initial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
notification that is required of all sources under the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
part 63 general provisions. After the Administrator or her 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
designee negotiates and approves these compliance measures 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
as part of the operating permit program, each source will 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have a specific set of requirements for which compliance can 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be determined by monitoring, observation and/or inspection. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=3 -->
D. Selection of Compliance Dates 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
The proposed rule would require that existing sources 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
comply within 1 year after the effective date of the rule. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
This provides time for shipyards and coating manufacturers 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to deplete most existing inventories of contemporary 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
coatings. An existing unaffected area source that increases 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
its emissions (or potential to emit) such that it becomes a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
major source would be required to comply within 1 year after 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
becoming a major source. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
