<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
H. Operating Permit Program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Under the operating permit regulations codified at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
40 CFR part 70, any source that is considered major under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Act or any nonmajor source subject to a standard under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sections 111 or 112 of the Act must obtain an operating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
permit [see &sect;70.3(a)(1)]. Often, emission limits, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
monitoring, and reporting and recordkeeping requirements are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
scattered among numerous provisions of State implementation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
plans or Federal regulations. As discussed in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
promulgated regulation for the operating permit program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
published on July 21, 1992 (57 FR 32250), this new permit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
program includes all of the air pollution control 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements that pertain to a single major stationary 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
source in a single document. Sources subject to the program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are required to submit complete permit applications within a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
year after a State operating permit program is approved by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the EPA; if a State program is not approved, sources will 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
submit applications to the EPA within a year after the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Federal program is promulgated. 
