disposed of at a site and require remediation under TSCA. In that case, the burden is on the site owner or operator to
establish, through persuasive evidence, that the PCBs are not illegally disposed of under TSCA. Today, EPA proposes
to address all PCB remediation waste, regardless of concentration, physical state or date of disposal (see proposed
introductory text at 761.60) under 761.61, based on the risk of exposure or injury they now pose. EPA would apply the
current ``anti-dilution'' provision at 761.1(b) to retain regulatory authority over PCB remediation waste even
where the PCB concentration is now below 50 ppm, unless the dilution was authorized (e.g., as the result of a transformer
reclassification under 761.30(a)(2)(v)) and the authorized dilution occurred prior to disposal. Anti-dilution
would not mandate disposal requirements for PCB remediation waste under proposed 761.61 (or 761.62 for PCB non-remediation
waste). Again, the burden would be on the site owner or operator to establish, through persuasive evidence, that the
PCB remediation wastes, regardless of current concentration or date of disposal are legally disposed of under TSCA
and in the case of wastes disposed of before April 18, 1978, which are now 
