used solvent, that could otherwise be safely and economically recycled by distillation within the laboratory, and
would also result in minimization of laboratory waste solvents for disposal. In addition, EPA is proposing to allow
the disposal of small quantities of non-liquid waste according to their existing (or presumed) concentration even
though that concentration is known to be the result of dilution from performance of chemical analysis. EPA believes
that the relatively small quantity of these wastes which are generated, their low concentrations of PCBs in non-liquid
materials, and the significant quantity of materials in the non-liquid waste which would absorb PCBs present make
disposal of these materials in a RCRA approved or TSCA approved landfill a safe and economical option. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 h. Transboundary movement of PCBs for disposal.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 EPA periodically receives requests from individuals wishing to import or export PCBs for disposal. Current regulations
at 40 CFR 761.20(b)(2), promulgated under section 6(e)(1) of TSCA, authorize the import or export for disposal of
PCBs only at concentrations less than 50 ppm. EPA believes there are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
instances where the import or export for disposal of PCBs at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
higher concentrations would not pose an unreasonable risk of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
injury to health or the environment. EPA therefore proposes to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
amend 761.20(b)(2) and add 761.20(b)(3) to create certain 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
categorical exceptions to the general ban on import for disposal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of PCBs at 50 ppm or greater and to clarify what constitutes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
import or export for purposes of this regulation. This proposal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would also establish a petition procedure under proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
761.20(b)(4) and (c)(3) under which other imports and exports 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for disposal could be allowed on a case-by-case basis. This 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section of the proposal would not alter the current ban on import 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or export of PCBs at 50 ppm or greater for purposes other than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal (including import for use, reuse, or recycling), or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
affect the meaning of the terms ``import'' or ``export'' for any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
other provisions of TSCA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 When EPA addressed the issue of import and export for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal in 1979, it noted that regulation of these types of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
activities could be accomplished under TSCA section 6(e)(1), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which governs disposal activities, or alternatively under section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6(e)(3), which governs manufacture and import activities (44 FR 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
31514, 31526 (May 31, 1979)). Based upon the authority in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section 6(e)(1), EPA elected to issue comprehensive regulations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that temporarily authorized the import and export of PCBs for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal, otherwise known as the ``Open Border Policy.'' EPA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
decided not to extend these regulations in 1980 and they expired 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(45 FR 29115 (May 1, 1980)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In 1984, EPA issued the current PCB regulations that address 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
import and export for disposal (40 CFR 761.20(b) and 761.60(h)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 761.60(h) provides that the import and export of PCBs and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
PCB Items for purposes of disposal are regulated under section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
761.20. Section 761.20(b)(2) authorizes only the import or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
export for disposal of PCBs at concentrations of less than 50 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ppm. The current rules do not authorize import or export for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal of PCBs at higher concentrations. In the absence of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
general rule that allows the import or export for disposal of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such PCBs, the only way that such wastes may currently be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
imported or exported is if EPA grants an exemption pursuant to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
TSCA section 6(e)(3). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
This rule is designed to control the transboundary movement of PCB waste in a manner consistent with the Basel Convention
on the Control of Transboundary Movement of Hazardous Wastes and their Disposal. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA is requesting comment on the circumstances under which 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the U.S. border should be opened to transboundary shipments of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
PCBs for disposal. The options range from allowing all imports 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for disposal under section 6(e) to maintaining the current closed border 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
status, and might include opening the border to PCBs from a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limited geographic area such as the Great Lakes drainage basin. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Today's proposal, if finalized, would retain the general 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
prohibitions on import and export of PCB wastes at concentrations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of 50 ppm or greater, with certain exceptions described below. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Import.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Proposed 761.20(b)(2) would allow three 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exceptions to the general prohibition on import of PCBs for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal. Proposed 761.20(b)(3) would clarify what 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
constitutes import for purposes of this regulation. EPA could 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
add categorical exceptions to proposed 761.20(b)(2) and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)(3) should the need arise in the future. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Imports of PCBs at concentrations less than 50 ppm. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Because the Administrator has made the finding that PCBs at concentrations less than 50 ppm present no unreasonable
risk to health or the environment, import for disposal of these PCBs would continue to be allowed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Import of PCB wastes from United States territories or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
possessions that are outside the customs territory of the United 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
States into the customs territory of the United States for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 TSCA and the regulations issued thereunder at 40 CFR Part 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
761 regulate the manufacture, import, distribution, processing, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
use, storage, and disposal of PCB waste in the United States. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The terms ``United States'' and ``States'' are defined at sections 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3(13) and 3(14) of TSCA to include ``any state, D.C., Puerto Rico, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Virgin Islands, Guam, the Canal Zone, American Samoa, Northern 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Mariana Islands, or any other territory or possession of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
United States.'' TSCA does not define imports specifically, but 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section 13 of TSCA requires the Secretary of the Treasury to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
refuse entry into the customs territory of the United States (as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
defined in general headnote 2 of the Tariff Schedules of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
United States) of any chemical substance, mixture, or article 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
offered for entry if it fails to comply with any rule under TSCA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In the Tariff Schedules, ``customs territory of the United States'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is defined as ``any State of the United States, the District of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Columbia, and Puerto Rico.'' Thus, a problem arises when a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
territory or possession which is outside the customs territory of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the United States attempts to ship PCB wastes back into the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
customs territory of the United States for disposal. Any such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
transfer of such PCB wastes at concentrations of 50 ppm or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
greater would be considered a prohibited import under existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulations. This is problematic because most United States 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
territories and possessions outside the customs territory do not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have adequate disposal facilities. Since PCBs persist in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
environment, improper disposal of PCBs in those territories or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
possessions could create an unreasonable risk to health or the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
environment in the territory or possession of the United States. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Therefore, EPA proposes to allow transfers of PCBs from United 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
States territories or possessions that are outside the customs 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
territory of the United States into the customs territory of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
United States for disposal. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 (3)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Imports of PCBs for disposal where EPA determines that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
it is in the interests of the United States and will not result 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in unreasonable risks to health or the environment. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 In addition to the categorical exceptions listed above, there may be instances in which it would be in the interests
of the United States to allow import of PCBs for disposal. This might be the case where PCBs were located outside the
United 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
States, but in close proximity to the United States, and adequate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal facilities were not available in the country in which 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
they were located. Import of the PCBs into the United States for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal might be in the interests of the United States to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
mitigate an unreasonable risk to health or the environment in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
United States that could not be mitigated by other means. It 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
might be in the interests of the United States to allow import of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
PCBs for disposal to implement a federal law such as CERCLA, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to carry out United States obligations under a treaty or other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
international agreement. EPA would not be inclined to find that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
import for disposal was in the interests of the United States 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
solely because disposal of the PCBs in this country was less 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
expensive. EPA proposes to allow imports for disposal that are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the interests of the United States on a case-by-case basis 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
where they would not pose an unreasonable risk of injury to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
health or the environment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Under its section 6(e)(1) authority to regulate disposal, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA proposes to allow these case-by-case exceptions to the ban on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
import for disposal of PCBs at concentrations of 50 ppm or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
greater at EPA's initiative or in response to a petition. Under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed 761.20(b)(4), any person may petition EPA for an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exception to the prohibition on import for disposal, and EPA may 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
grant such an exception if it finds that to do so would be in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
interests of the United States and would not result in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
unreasonable risk of injury to health or the environment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Petitions would be filed with the Director, Chemical 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Management Division. The Director has the authority to issue 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
TSCA PCB disposal approvals in certain instances and is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responsible for coordination and oversight of PCB disposal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
activities in the United States. Therefore, the Director is in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the most advantageous position to require proper disposal of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
imported PCBs. Petitions would have to be submitted on an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
individual basis for each individual that would be subject to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exception. If EPA determined that it was appropriate to create a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
categorical exception, it could do so by adding through 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rulemaking to the categorical exceptions proposed at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
761.20(b)(2) and (b)(3). Information to be included in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
petition is specified at proposed 761.20(b)(4)(i) through (vii). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The petitioner would be notified of EPA's decision by letter. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
To implement the proposed 761.20(b)(2) through (4), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA is also proposing at 761.20(b)(5) that all PCBs at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
concentrations greater than or equal to 50 ppm that are imported 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for disposal must be disposed of in an EPA designated facility 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which has a TSCA PCB disposal approval. Each facility's TSCA PCB 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal approval would have to contain specific conditions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
addressing at a minimum its designation to receive specified 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
shipments of imported PCBs for disposal, analytical data on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
wastes to be imported including their compatibility with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
facility's approved waste disposal techniques, prior notification 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and certification to EPA of adequate disposal capacity, use of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the manifest system, provisions for financial responsibility for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the imported PCBs from the port of entry through final disposal, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
appropriate recordkeeping for these activities, and any other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
conditions that EPA found were necessary to ensure that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
import and disposal of PCBs did not present an unreasonable risk 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of injury to health or the environment. Since EPA cannot easily 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reach foreign generators of imported PCBs to enforce liability 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provisions of TSCA or other Federal statutes and cannot be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
assured that shipments of imported PCBs could be returned to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
their country of origin if they could not be disposed of at the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
designated facility, conditions would be included in disposal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
approvals to address these situations. Imported PCBs could also 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be decontaminated under the proposed changes to 761.79. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
However, the PCBs would have to be imported to a commercial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
storage facility which had a PCB commercial storage approval, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
unless exempt, including special approval conditions for imported 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
wastes, as noted above. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Export.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 When EPA announced the expiration of the Open 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Border Policy in 1980 it stated, with regard to exports, that it 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would not grant an exemption unless the nation to which the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
export was destined had proper facilities for ultimate disposal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(See 45 FR 29115). EPA believes that export of PCBs to other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
countries needs to be limited so as not to pose a risk of injury to
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
health or the environment in those countries and that to the maximum 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
extent practicable, each nation should manage its own waste within its 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
own borders. Therefore, EPA is proposing at 761.20(c)(3) to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
allow export for disposal of PCB waste at concentrations of 50 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ppm or greater on a case-by-case basis unless EPA has reason to believe that the PCBs in question will not be properly
managed, where the receiving 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
country has an international agreement consistent with the international obligations of the United States relating
to transboundary movements of PCBs and their disposal, with the U.S. Government concerning such exports; the government
of the receiving country certifies to EPA that it has received accurate and complete information about the waste,
consents to receive it, and has adequate disposal facilities to assure proper management; and the exporter identifies
waste containing liquid PCBs or PCB-containing electrical 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
equipment. As an example, vessels are sometimes exported for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
salvage of the considerable amounts of metal they contain. PCBs 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
present in integral components of the ships, such as wire cable 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or air handling system gaskets, could be exported with the ship 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under conditions specified in the export approval. EPA could 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
require as a condition of approval for export that PCBs found in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
large capacitors, transformers, and hydraulic or heat transfer 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fluids, be removed prior to export for disposal. EPA could allow 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such exports for disposal on its own initiative or in response to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a petition. Other information that would have to be included in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the petition is set out at proposed 761.20(c)(3). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Other transboundary shipments.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Certain types of movement of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
PCB wastes accross national borders is not considered to be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
either import or export. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Transport of PCB waste generated in the United States 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
through a foreign country (and any residuals resulting from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cleanup of spills of such waste in transit) for reentry into the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
United States for disposal. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The proposal would clarify that PCB waste generated in the United States may be transported through a foreign country
and returned to the United States for disposal. For example, PCB 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
waste generated in Michigan could be transported across Canada 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for disposal in New York. Any residual PCB waste resulting from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the cleanup of spills that might occur in transit could also be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
brought into the United States for disposal. Otherwise, it would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be impractical and inefficient to transport PCBs generated in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
certain parts of the United States to nearby United States 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disposal facilities. This provision is included in 761.20(b)(3) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
as a clarification. For purposes of this regulation, EPA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
considers such shipments to be transit shipments, not exports or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
imports. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Return for disposal of wastes that result from PCBs that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
were procured domestically by the U. S. Government, taken 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
overseas for use by the U. S. Government, and that have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
remained under U. S. Government control since the time of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
procurement (including any residuals resulting from cleanup of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
spills of such wastes during use, storage, or in transit).
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 In conjunction with U. S. Government operations, PCBs may be taken to United States facilities abroad for use. Because
these PCBs have always been the property of the United States, and because disposal facilities for these wastes might

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not be readily available overseas, they would be permitted back 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
into the United States for disposal along with any residuals 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
resulting from cleanup of spills occurring during use, while in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
storage for reuse or awaiting shipment for disposal, or in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
transit. For purposes of this regulation, EPA would not consider 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
these shipments to be exports or imports. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
i.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Landfilling of liquid PCBs.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 EPA proposes to remove the provisions allowing for the disposal of liquid PCBs, which have been stabilized on-site
prior to disposal, at a chemical waste landfill, 761.60(a)(2)(ii), 761.60(a)(3)(ii), and 761.75(b)(8)(ii). These
provisions were established in the May 31, 1979 rulemaking, since at the time of the rulemaking there was a limited
number of incinerators permitted to burn PCB waste and disposal capacity was a concern. Currently, and as can be reasonably
expected in the future, the amount of low concentration PCB liquids anticipated to be designated for disposal and
in storage for disposal can easily be accommodated within the existing and anticipated future PCB disposal technologies
other than landfilling. The existing PCB disposal and storage for disposal regulations and the amendments proposed
in this rulemaking are expected to accommodate the surplus in the disposal capacity supply. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Further support for this deletion of a disposal option for liquid PCBs having low PCB concentrations is the prohibition
on landfilling liquid hazardous wastes containing PCBs under the RCRA land disposal restrictions at 40 CFR 268.42.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
j.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Self-Implementing requirements for research and development for PCB disposal activities_ 1. General
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. This change would eliminate the time-consuming process of obtaining an R&amp;D approval in order to engage in limited
R&amp;D into PCB disposal. R&amp;D for PCB disposal not conforming with the limitations of this section would require
written approval or written waiver of the requirements of a 761.60(e), 761.60(i)(2), or 761.70(a) or (b) approval
by the Regional Administrator in the EPA Region where the R&amp;D would occur. Persons engaged in research and development
into PCB disposal technologies would now be required to obtain an EPA identification number. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA proposes at 761.60(j) a self-implementing approval for research and development (R&amp;D) for PCB disposal
activities. Limitations are proposed for the amount of PCB material disposed of, the concentration of the PCBs disposed
of, the total amount of PCBs, and the duration of the R&amp;D for disposal activity. All treated and untreated PCB materials
from a PCB R&amp;D for disposal activity would be required to be disposed of according to 761.60(a)-(e). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Definition of R&amp;D for PCB Disposal.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 An individual engaged in R&amp;D for PCB disposal activities is someone who is not accepting PCB waste on a commercial
scale; the person is involved solely in the R&amp;D for preliminary investigation and limited scale up of PCB disposal
technologies and may or may not possess a TSCA PCB R&amp;D Approval issued according to 761.60(e), 761.60(i)(2),
or 761.70(a) or (b). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Limitations.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 EPA is proposing at 761.60(j) that the maximum quantity used annually under this exemption for PCB treatability study
samples be 70 cubic feet for solid material or 500 gallons for liquid material. This should be a sufficient amount of
material for conducting small-scale treatability studies. If additional material is needed to conduct the study,
the Regional Administrator may at his or her discretion grant requests on a case-by-case basis for quantity limits
in excess of those specified or require a formal R&amp;D approval if the increased quantity could present an unreasonable
risk to health or the environment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In addition to a quantity cut-off, EPA is proposing at 761.60(j) to limit the maximum concentration for PCB waste that
is used in a treatability study to 10,000 ppm for those utilizing the 500 gallon or 70 cubic feet volume cap or 1 kilogram
(kg) of pure PCB waste annually at the facility. It has been EPA's experience in the past in reviewing applications
for R&amp;D approvals and in discussions with those in the waste treatment field, that it is rare that one would need
a sample that contains more than 10,000 ppm PCBs to conduct a small-scale treatability study. The concentration limits
are also proposed based on the Agency's concern with the potential risks associated with the distribution in commerce
(without a manifest) and handling of high concentration PCBs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA is also limiting the approvals under proposed 761.60(j) to one calendar year to evaluate the progress and scope
of the R&amp;D and to plan for potential formal permitting of successful technologies. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
